TY  - JOUR
T1  - Executive Job Demands: Suggestions from a Stress and Decision-Making Perspective
AU  - Ganster, Daniel C.
Y1  - 2005/07/01
PY  - 2005
DA  - 2005/07/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2005.17293366
DO  - 10.5465/amr.2005.17293366
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 492
EP  - 502
VL  - 30
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Hambrick, Finkelstein, and Mooney advance propositions concerning the effects of job demands on executive leadership and decision-making behaviors. I aim to encourage further thinking in this area, with comments flowing from a consideration of the stress and decision-making literature and the positive affect and problem-solving behavior literature. This perspective suggests both a finer-grained conceptualization of the executive job demands construct informed by specific characteristics of decision problems and a finer-grained conceptualization of executive decision behaviors focused on elements reflecting correspondence and coherence outcomes of decisions.
AB  - Hambrick, Finkelstein, and Mooney advance propositions concerning the effects of job demands on executive leadership and decision-making behaviors. I aim to encourage further thinking in this area, with comments flowing from a consideration of the stress and decision-making literature and the positive affect and problem-solving behavior literature. This perspective suggests both a finer-grained conceptualization of the executive job demands construct informed by specific characteristics of decision problems and a finer-grained conceptualization of executive decision behaviors focused on elements reflecting correspondence and coherence outcomes of decisions.
