TY  - JOUR
T1  - Executive Job Demands: New Insights for Explaining Strategic Decisions and Leader Behaviors
AU  - Hambrick, Donald C.
AU  - Finkelstein, Sydney
AU  - Mooney, Ann C.
Y1  - 2005/07/01
PY  - 2005
DA  - 2005/07/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2005.17293355
DO  - 10.5465/amr.2005.17293355
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 472
EP  - 491
VL  - 30
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Executive jobs vary widely in the difficulty they pose for their incumbents, yet research on top executives and strategic decision making has largely ignored this reality. We build on work in industrial/organizational psychology to develop the construct of executive job demands; discuss its major determinants; propose some of its key implications for strategic choices and leadership behaviors; and propose the usefulness of this construct in advancing research on numerous fronts, including agency theory, executive compensation, and upper echelons.
AB  - Executive jobs vary widely in the difficulty they pose for their incumbents, yet research on top executives and strategic decision making has largely ignored this reality. We build on work in industrial/organizational psychology to develop the construct of executive job demands; discuss its major determinants; propose some of its key implications for strategic choices and leadership behaviors; and propose the usefulness of this construct in advancing research on numerous fronts, including agency theory, executive compensation, and upper echelons.
SN  - 0363-7425
M3  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2005.17293355
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/amr.2005.17293355
Y2  - 2026/04/24
