TY  - JOUR
T1  - Territoriality in Organizations
AU  - Brown, Graham
AU  - Lawrence, Thomas B.
AU  - Robinson, Sandra L.
Y1  - 2005/07/01
PY  - 2005
DA  - 2005/07/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2005.17293710
DO  - 10.5465/amr.2005.17293710
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 577
EP  - 594
VL  - 30
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Territorial feelings and behaviors are important, pervasive, and yet largely overlooked aspects of organizational life. Organizational members can and do become territorial over physical spaces, ideas, roles, relationships, and other potential possessions in organizations. We examine how territorial behaviors are used to construct, communicate, maintain, and restore territories in organizations. We then go on to discuss the organizational consequences of these behaviors, including their effects on organizational commitment, conflict, preoccupation, and individual isolation.
AB  - Territorial feelings and behaviors are important, pervasive, and yet largely overlooked aspects of organizational life. Organizational members can and do become territorial over physical spaces, ideas, roles, relationships, and other potential possessions in organizations. We examine how territorial behaviors are used to construct, communicate, maintain, and restore territories in organizations. We then go on to discuss the organizational consequences of these behaviors, including their effects on organizational commitment, conflict, preoccupation, and individual isolation.
